<lb n="6"/>mahā<unclear>de</unclear>vyāṁ dhruvadevyām utpannasya mahārājādhirāja-śrī-kumāraguptasyābhivarddhamāna-vijaya-rājya-saṁvatsare ṣaṇ-ṇavate
</p>
        <p><lb n="7"/><supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->a</supplied><unclear>syā</unclear><sic>
            <unclear>n</unclear>
          </sic> <unclear>di</unclear>vasa-pūrvvāyāṁ bhagavatas trailokya-tejas-saṁbhāra-saṁ<unclear>bhr̥</unclear>tādbhuta-mūrtter brahmaṇya-devasya<!-- 
Bhandarkar supplies a for asyām, but I can't even see if there is a character there. We could equally well assume the a was dropped in sandhi (compare āyatane smin in l8). Cunningham's eye copy, though, shows an a there; also, it reads asyā divasa, so if correct, we should read (syāṁ di) instead of (syān di). 
--><!-- 
Fleet's original reading was saṁtatādbhuta. Bhandarkar prints sam(bhr̥)tādbhuta, with m instead of anusvāra. This seems to be a typo; otherwise, I think bhr̥ is slightly more likely than ta. #Agrawal_1940:59 suggests saṁbhūta, and so does Agrawal_1986:28. I think saṁbhr̥ta is again better. 
--><lb n="8"/><gap precision="low" quantity="4" reason="illegible" unit="character"/>-<unclear>n</unclear>ivāsinaḥ svāmi-mahāsenasyāyatane smin kārtta-yugācāra-saddharmma-vartmānuyāyinā|<!-- 
Bhandarkar prints a daṇḍa at the end of l8. There is a horizontal, slightly down-slanted stroke after nā which may be more than a random scratch in the stone. There is another uncalled-for daṇḍa at the end of l9, and thereafter, daṇḍas mark the ends of half-stanzas. Cunningham has no daṇḍa here, but does show a horizontal, curved stroke at the end of l9 and subsequent loci. 
--><!-- 
These daṇḍas suggest that l8-9 may have been intended as verse too, but I can't make out any regularity in its metre, either syllabic or moraic. (The words dhruvaśarmmaṇā karmma mahat kr̥tedam match one line of a metre called kamalā, but we'd need to read parṣadi mānitena to get part of the same pattern in the previous line, and the inscription is definitely dā. Also, there is probably no room in this line to fit 4 lines of 12 syllables each.) 
--><lb n="9"/><seg subtype="consonant" type="component">
            <gap quantity="1" reason="illegible" unit="component"/>
          </seg><unclear>āta</unclear> <gap precision="low" quantity="12" reason="illegible" unit="character"/> <supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->pa</supplied>rṣadā mānitena dhruvaśarmmaṇā karmma mahat <choice>
            <sic>kr̥tedaM</sic>
            <corr>kr̥tam idaM</corr>
          </choice><unclear>|</unclear><!-- 
At the beginning of this line, Cunningham's eye copy reads vetaccha; it also shows "(sa) #?2# ri#aula" before parṣadā. 
--><!-- 
This daṇḍa is indiscernible in the facsimile, along with the m, so I can't tell for sure if it's a subscript one. 
--></p>
        <lg met="sragdharā" n="1">
          <l n="a"><lb n="10"/><unclear>kr̥tvā</unclear> <seg met="+">
              <gap quantity="1" reason="illegible" unit="character"/>
            </seg> <unclear>ā</unclear>bhirāmāṁ muni<unclear>-vasati</unclear> <seg met="-+">
              <gap quantity="2" reason="illegible" unit="character"/>
            </seg> svargga-sopāna-r<unclear>ū</unclear>pām<!-- 
Cunningham's eye copy reads śivābhirāmā (no anusvāra) at the first lacuna, which is unmetrical, but could perhaps be read as śaivābhirāmāṁ. 
--><!-- 
For the second lacuna, Cunningham has munidamanidhitaṁ (printed as -dhitiam on page 19, but dhitaṁ in the eye copy. The character he transcribes as dha looks more like e (except for the I mātrā) and could be a number of other things in his eye copy.) My own conjecture would be munivasatim imāṁ, but the eye copy, if reliable to any degree, does not confirm this. (Sircar's conjecture is munivasatim iha). 
--></l>
          <l n="b">kaubera-cchanda-bimbāṁ sphaṭika-maṇi-dalābhāsa-gaurāṁ pratolī<unclear>M|</unclear><!-- 
Bhandarkar prints m at the end of this line; Cunningham's eye copy has anusvāra. Nothing after lī is discernible in the facsimile. 
--></l>
          <l n="c"><lb n="11"/>prāsādā<unclear>grābhi</unclear>rūpaṁ gu<unclear>ṇa-va</unclear>ra-bhavanaṁ <unclear>dharmma-sa</unclear>ttraṁ <unclear>ya</unclear>thāvaT<!-- 
Cunningham's eye copy has puṇya (followed by largely illegible traces) instead of guṇa. Unmetrical. Also, he shows a horizontal line above the halanta t, which may be part of the character, or it may be a punctuation mark as in line 13 - maybe the text has punctuation marks after every quarter, not just after half-verses? 
--></l>
          <l n="d">pu<unclear>ṇ</unclear>yeṣv evābhirāmaṁ vrajati śubha-matis tāta-śarmmā dhruvo stu|<!-- 
The punctuation sign is a downcurving horizontal dash that may be crossed by a vertical line or squiggle. 
--></l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="śārdūlavikrīḍita" n="2">
          <l n="a"><lb n="12"/><seg subtype="consonant" type="component">
              <gap quantity="1" reason="illegible" unit="component"/>
            </seg><unclear>ā</unclear><seg subtype="consonant" type="component">
              <gap quantity="1" reason="illegible" unit="component"/>
            </seg><unclear>ī</unclear> <seg met="+">
              <gap quantity="1" reason="illegible" unit="character"/>
            </seg> sya <seg met="-+">
              <gap quantity="2" reason="illegible" unit="character"/>
            </seg> śubhāmr̥ta-vara-prakhyāta-labdhā bhuvi</l>
          <!-- 
Bhandarkar prints the ā and ī at the beginning as clear, but I can't even make out if he sees those on the first and second characters or somewhere else. Cunningham has vyātīr#asya #2# gasa yatavara for the beginning of the line. On the basis of his eye copy, I'm pretty confident that the correct reading is khyātir yasya. 
-->
